{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514390"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:21:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:21:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12312"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12312","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12312"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.51,0.05,0.04,0.37,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4833"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107601"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4833"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12312"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90050"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1287"},{"type":"tags","id":"1708"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"3310"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"3980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4626"},{"type":"tags","id":"5937"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7779"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9311"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26740"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31021"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46061"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107601"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man is brought to the Emergency Department by his sister with sudden onset of right-sided weakness, difficulty speaking and confusion. The sister reports that these symptoms began while he was watching television at home and have been present for one hour. He has no medical history and does not take any regular medications. He seldom smokes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 112/min, blood pressure 170/110 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. He has right-sided hemiparesis and expressive dysphasia. He also has trouble following three-stage commands.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal CT brain, CT angiogram and CT perfusion which showed a hyperdense sign in the left middle cerebral artery (MCA) and confirmed the large vessel occlusion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation to identify the underlying cause?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Echocardiogram","Complement levels","CT chest/abdomen/pelvis","Carotid ultrasound","Electroencephalogram"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s clinical presentation of sudden onset of right-sided hemiparesis and dysphasia is consistent with an ischaemic stroke. The hyperdense sign in the left MCA on CT brain confirms the diagnosis of acute ischaemic stroke. Young patients with stroke require additional extensive testing to determine the underlying predisposition to stroke, or aetiology, as the standard risk factors of age, hypertension, atrial fibrillation and diabetes mellitus do not usually apply to young people with strokes. Young people with stroke are screened for rarer causes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA transthoracic \u003Cstrong\u003Eechocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate investigation to identify potential cardiac sources of paradoxical embolism, including a patent foramen ovale, which is a common cardiac abnormality that can cause cryptogenic strokes, such as in this scenario, where there is no readily identifiable cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplement levels\u003C/strong\u003E are not part of the standard \u0022young stroke\u0022 work up. Complement levels may be low in patients with suspected autoimmune diseases like vasculitis or systemic lupus erythematosus. Generally, thrombophilia screens are done as part of a \u0022young stroke\u0022 work up.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan chest/abdomen/pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E is part of standard malignancy work up. This investigation is often completed after a patient experiences an unprovoked venous thromboembolism. It is not completed in the case of an unprovoked stroke, as while malignancy is prothrombotic, it does not often increase the risk of ischaemic stroke.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarotid ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is used to assess the carotid arteries for stenosis or dissection that could cause stroke. However, in this case, the CT angiogram already performed would have visualised both intracranial and extracranial vessels, including the carotid arteries. Since the CT angiogram has already provided comprehensive vascular imaging and identified the site of occlusion, a carotid ultrasound would not add additional diagnostic value at this stage. The focus should now shift to identifying non-vascular causes of stroke in this young patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eelectroencephalogram\u003C/strong\u003E records electrical activity in the brain and can be helpful in identifying seizure activity. It is not part of the young stroke work up.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["All young strokes should have an echocardiogram to look for a patent foramen ovale.","Young patients with stroke require additional testing to determine underlying causes, as standard risk factors may not apply."],"references":["Stack CA, Cole JW. The Clinical Approach to Stroke in Young Adults. In: Dehkharghani S, editor. Stroke [Internet]. Brisbane (AU): Exon Publications; 2021 Jun 18. Chapter 3. PMID: 34279884. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34279884/","Nakanishi K, Homma S. Role of echocardiography in patients with stroke. J Cardiol. 2016 Aug;68(2):91-9. doi: 10.1016/j.jjcc.2016.05.001. Epub 2016 May 30. PMID: 27256218. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27256218/","Aggeli C, Verveniotis A, Andrikopoulou E, Vavuranakis E, Toutouzas K, Tousoulis D. Echocardiographic features of PFOs and paradoxical embolism: a complicated puzzle. Int J Cardiovasc Imaging. 2018 Dec;34(12):1849-1861. doi: 10.1007/s10554-018-1406-1. Epub 2018 Jun 28. PMID: 29956022. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29956022/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90050"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12312"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90050","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90050"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-01T10:35:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-01T10:39:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4833"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107601"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tag